{"summary":"All three amendments identify real integrity defects in the milestone/task-run filesystem model: hidden milestone IDs can collide with reserved storage, completion matching can finalize the wrong attempt, and named retries can leave contradictory stale running history behind.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-16-381b2bc1","decision":"accept","rationale":"`MilestoneId::new()` currently permits dot-prefixed single-segment names even though milestone listing skips dot-prefixed directories and lock storage reserves `milestones/.locks/`. That creates a concrete namespace collision for `.locks` and allows milestones that normal enumeration cannot see, so rejecting dot-prefixed IDs is the right invariant."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-20005d1b","decision":"accept","rationale":"When a completion supplies `run_id`, `update_task_run` should only finalize that exact attempt. The current fallback to a lone unfinished runless row is no longer safely disambiguated because `record_bead_completion` no longer passes `started_at`, so it can silently attach a new named retry’s completion to the wrong older attempt and corrupt lineage."},{"amendment_id":"fr-16-20943f79","decision":"accept","rationale":"Starting a new explicit `run_id` while an older runless row remains open currently leaves two live histories for the same bead, and `find_runs_for_bead` can then report an older attempt still `running` after a later retry already `succeeded`. That is internally inconsistent audit state; the start path should either supersede the stale legacy attempt or reject the retry until the old row is resolved."}]}